'''Yamhad''' (also written '''Yamkhad''' or '''Jamhad''') was an ancient [[Levant]]ine kingdom centered at <U+1E24>alab (or <U+1E24>alba), modern day [[Aleppo]], [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=5MYFOWRZ8Z4C&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The pre-Islamic Middle East|author=Martin Sicker|page=26|year=2000}}</ref> The kingdom was ruled by the [[Yamhad dynasty]] and the people were predominately [[Amorites]] with a substantial [[Hurrian]] population who settled in the kingdom, adding the influence of their culture. 

An important religious and trade center, Yamhad was powerful during the early [[Bronze Age]]. Its biggest rivals were [[Assyria#Amorite Period in Assyria.2C 1809.E2.80.931750 BC|Assyria]] to the East and [[Qatna]] to the south. Yamhad dominated northern, northwestern and eastern Syria and had influence over small kingdoms in Mesopotamia at the borders of [[Elam]]. It was eventually destroyed by the [[Hittites]], then annexed by [[Mitanni]] in the 16th century&nbsp;BC.

Little of Halab has been excavated by archaeologists as Halab was never abandoned during its long history and the modern city is situated above the ancient site.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=YqNvQgAACAAJ&dq|title=History of Ancient Levant (part 1) Syria|author= Ahmad Arhim Hebbo|page=30|year=1993}}</ref> Therefore, most of the knowledge about Yamhad comes from tablets discovered at [[Alalakh]] and [[Mari, Syria|Mari]].

==History==
 
===Establishment===
The name Yamhad was likely an Amorite tribal name and is used synonymously with Halab when referring to the kingdom.<ref name="Gordon" /><ref name="john">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=6TwiY96cunQC&pg=PA388#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Inscriptions of the Iron Age: Part 1|author=John David Hawkins| page=388|year= 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=P5q7DDqMbF0C&pg=PA781#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Companion to the Archaeology of the Ancient Near East|author=D. T. Potts| page=781|year= 2012}}</ref> The city of Halab has been a religious center in northern Syria since the times of [[Ebla]], when it was mentioned as a vassal with the name of '''Ha-lam'''.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=hFRwonqqNCUC&pg=PA250#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Orientalia: Vol. 63|author= alfonso archi|page= 250|year= 1994}}</ref> Halab fame as a [[Holy City]] contributed to its later prominence,<ref name="Llu<U+00ED>s">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=IN9_IRYKKUMC&pg=PA192#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The God Dagan in Bronze Age Syria|author= Llu<U+00ED>s Feliu|page=192|year= 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=hM8UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Diss Ertationes : The Conflict Between El and Ba'al in Canaanite Religion|author= Ulf Oldenburg|page=65|year= 1969}}</ref> the main temple of the storm god [[Hadad]] was located on top of the citadel hill in the center of the city,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=Xno9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce| page=111|year= 2014}}</ref> and the city was known as the '''City of Hadad'''.<ref name="Llu<U+00ED>s" /> Ebla which controlled most of northern Syria was destroyed twice at the end of the 3rd millennium,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=9bbgJzacoJYC&pg=PA253#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=6 ICAANE|author= Paolo Matthiae, Licia Romano| page=253|year= 2010}}</ref> and the [[power vacuum]] in the region caused by its fall paved the way for Halab later rise.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=8MrcXuVmi1QC&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Whisper of Stone: Natib Qadish: Modern Canaanite Religion|author= Tess Dawson| page=13|year= 2009}}</ref> 

The name Halab as well as that of Yamhad appeared for the first time during the [[Babylonia#First Babylonian Dynasty .E2.80.94_Amorite Dynasty 1894.E2.80.931595 BC|Old Babylonian]] period,<ref name="john" /> when [[Sumu-Epuh]] the first Yamhadite king was attested in a seal from [[Mari, Syria|Mari]] as the ruler of the land of Yamhad,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=u2nUT_RtyQ8C&pg=PA780#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Old Babylonian Period (2003-1595 BC)|author=Douglas Frayne| page=780|year= 1990}}</ref> which included in addition to Halab the cities of [[Alalakh]] and [[Umm el-Marra|Tuba]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=74JI2UlcU8AC&pg=PA10&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=International Dictionary of Historic Places: Southern Europe|author=  Trudy Ring,Robert M. Salkin,Sharon La Boda| page=10|year= 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=2aq43z3at0wC&pg=PA376#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Opening the Tablet Box: Near Eastern Studies in Honor of Benjamin R. Foster|author= Sarah Melville,Alice Slotsky| page=376}}</ref> Sumu-Epuh consolidated the kingdom and faced [[Yahdun-Lim]] of Mari who had a [[Royal intermarriage|dynastic alliance]] with Yamhad to oppose Assyria,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=_EtJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT354#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Ancient Near East: History, Society and Economy|author=  Mario Liverani| page=354|year= 2013}}</ref> but eventually campaigned in the north threatening the kingdom.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=Oy4xUpsa7DkC&pg=PA128#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Challenging Climate Change: Competition and Cooperation Among Pastoralists and Agriculturalists in Northern Mesopotamia|author= Arne Wossink| page=128}}</ref> The Yamhadite king supported the [[Yaminite]] tribes and formed an alliance with other Syrian states including [[Tuttul]], [[Urshu]], [[Khashshum|Hassum]] and [[Carchemish]],<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=KYxxmRoTfsQC&pg=PA45&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Military Establishments at Mari|author= Jack M. Sasson| page=45|year= 1969}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=aaDtAAAAMAAJ&q|title= A Political History of Eshnunna, Mari and Assyria During the Early Old Babylonian Period: From the End of Ur III to the Death of <U+0160>am<U+0161>i-Adad|author= Yuhong Wu| page=131|year= 1994}}</ref> against the Mariote king who defeated his enemies,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=u2nUT_RtyQ8C&pg=PA606&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Old Babylonian Period (2003-1595 BC)|author= Douglas Frayne| page=606}}</ref> but was eventually killed by his son Sumu-Yamam.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=4DVHJRFW3mYC&pg=PT68&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Oxford History of the Biblical World|author= Michael David Coogan| page=68|year= 2001}}</ref>

===Rivalry with Assyria and Expansion===
The rise of [[Shamshi-Adad I]] of Assyria proved more dangerous to Yamhad than Mari, the Assyrian king was an ambitious conqueror with the aim to rule [[Mesopotamia]] and the Levant calling himself king of the World.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=0H0EpSm8aioC&pg=PA9#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Cultures in Contact: From Mesopotamia to the Mediterranean in the Second Millennium BC|author= Joan Aruz, Sarah B. Graff, and Yelena Rakic| page=9|year= 2013}}</ref> Shamshi-Adad surrounded Yamhad by alliances with Charchemish, Hassum and Urshu to the north and by conquering Mari to the east forcing [[Zimri-Lim]] the heir of Mari to flee. Sumu-Epuh welcomed Zimri-Limand aimed to use him against Assyria since he was the legitimate heir of Mari.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=4DVHJRFW3mYC&pg=PT68#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Oxford History of the Biblical World|author= Michael David Coogan| page=68|year= 2001}}</ref> 
[[File:Cuneiform legal tablet in case from Aleppo.jpg|thumb|160px|Legal case from Niqmi-Epuh, to the king of Alalakh concerning the legacy of two houses]]
Shamshi-Adad most dangerous alliance was with [[Qatna]] whose king [[Ishi-Adad]] became Assyria agent at Yamhad borders and married his daughter to [[Yasmah-Adad]], the son of the Assyrian king who was installed by his father as king of Mari.<ref name="Mario">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=0d1JAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA234#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Ancient Near East: History, Society and Economy|author= Mario Liverani| page=234|year= 2013}}</ref> Sumu-Epuh was apparently killed during his fight with Shamshi-Adad and was succeeded by his son [[Yarim-Lim I]],<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=E1aF0hq1GR8C&pg=PA773#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Routledge Handbook of the Peoples and Places of Ancient Western Asia: The Near East from the Early Bronze Age to the Fall of the Persian Empire|author= Trevor Bryce|page=773|year= 2009}}</ref> who cemented his father kingdom and turned it into the most powerful kingdom in Syria and northern Mesopotamia.<ref name="Dalley" /><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=kiWD_5PRQBUC&pg=PA383#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Semitic and Assyriological Studies|author= Pelio Fronzaroli|page=383|year= 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=4DVHJRFW3mYC&pg=PT70#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Oxford History of the Biblical World|author= Michael David Coogan|page=70|year= 2001}}</ref> Yarim-Lim surrounded Shamshi-Adad by alliances with [[Hammurabi]] of Babylon and [[Ibal-pi-el II]] of [[Eshnunna]],<ref name="hamblin">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=biyDDd0uKGMC&pg=254&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Warfare in the Ancient Near East to 1600 BC: Holy Warriors at the Dawn of History |author= William J. Hamblin|page=254|year= 2006}}</ref> then in 1777 BC he advanced to the east conquering Tuttul and installing Zimri-Lim as governor of the city.<ref name="hamblin" /> The death of the Assyrian king came a year later, Yarim-Lim then sent his army with Zimri-Lim to restore his ancestors throne as a vassal to Yamhad,<ref name="hamblin" /> and the relation was cemented through a dynastic marriage between the new Mariote king and [[Shibtu]] the daughter of Yarim-Lim.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=i4jBn3cThwgC&pg=PA257#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Oxford Handbook of Cuneiform Culture|author= Karen Radner,Eleanor Robson|page=257|year= 2011}}</ref> 

Yarim-Lim spent the next years of his reign subduing other Syrian city-states through alliances or force, [[Ebla]] and [[Ugarit]] were allied to Yamhad,<ref name="Gordon" /><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=8qvY8pxVxcwC&pg=PA61#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= A Comparative Study of Thirty City-state Cultures: An Investigation, Volume 21|author= Mogens Herman Hansen|page=61|year= 2000}}</ref> while [[Qatna]] was forced into peace, as it has lost its ally the late Shamshi-Adad I and was left alone in the face of Yamhad.<ref name="Mario" /><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=4DVHJRFW3mYC&pg=PT71#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Oxford History of the Biblical World|author= Michael David Coogan|page=71|year= 2001}}</ref> A sample of Yarim-Lim policy of diplomacy and war can be read in a tablet discovered at Mari that was sent to the king of [[Der (Sumer)|D<U+0113>r]] in southern Mesopotamia, which included a declaration of war against Der and its neighbor [[Diniktum]],<ref name="jak">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=J8GgNzv1LfsC&pg=PA2#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Military Establishments at Mari|author= Jack M. Sasson|page=2|year= 1969}}</ref> the tablet mentions the stationing of 500 Yamhadite warships for twelve years in Diniktum and the Yamhadite military support of Der for 15 years.<ref name="jak" /> Yarim-Lim accomplishments elevated Yamhad into the status of a Great Kingdom and the Yamhadite king title became the [[Great King]].<ref name="Gordon" /><ref name="Mario" /> A tablet from the archives of Mari mentions the extensive authority that Yamhad had ''':'''

{{cquote|There is no king who is mighty by himself. Ten or fifteen kings follow [[Hammurabi]] the ruler of [[Babylon]], a like number of Rim-Sin of [[Larsa]], a like number of Ibal-pi-el of [[Eshnunna]], a like number of Amud-pi-el of [[Qatna|Qatanum]], but twenty follow Yarim-Lim of Yamhad.<ref name="Dalley" />}}

Yarim-Lim I was succeeded by his son [[Hammurabi I]] who had a peaceful reign,<ref name="hamblin" /> he was able to force Charchemish into submission,<ref name="hamblin" /> and sent troops to aid Hammurabi of Babylon against [[Larsa]] and [[Elam]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=eCO17x85ymgC&pg=PA102#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Writing, Law, and Kingship in Old Babylonian Mesopotamia|author= Dominique Charpin| page=102|year= 2010}}</ref> The alliance ended after the Babylonian king sacked Mari and destroyed it, however Babylon didn't attack Yamhad and the relations between the two kingdoms remained peaceful during the later years.<ref name="Mario" /> [[Abba-El I]] son of Hammurabi I continued his father policy, during his reign a rebellion by Zitraddu governor of [[Irridu]] against Abbal-El brother [[Yarim-Lim of Alalakh|Yarim-Lim]] was quashed and the city destroyed, Abba-El compensated his brother by giving him the throne of Alalakh.<ref name="hamblin" />

===Decline and End===
[[File:God Head Djabul Louvre AO10831.jpg|thumb|160px|God head discovered near [[Sabkhat al-Jabbul|Jabbul]] (c. 1600 BC)<ref>[http://www.louvre.fr/en/oeuvre-notices/head-god jabbul head louvre]</ref> ]]
[[Yarim-Lim III]] imposed Yamhad hegemony over Qatna, but the fortunes of Yamhad started to faint with the [[Hittites]] kingdom rising in the north. The weakening was obvious as Alalakh had became virtually independent under [[Ammitakum]] who declared himself king but not independent.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=7TcJAQAAIAAJ&q=ammitakum&dq=ammitakum&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zzvhUqCkM8OqhQfwsIGoCw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAjgK|title= Archaeology and Old Testament study: jubilee volume of the Society for Old Testament Study, 1917-1967|author= THOMAS, D. WINTON| page=121}}</ref> In spite of this regression, the king of Halab remained the mightiest king of the Syrian states as he was referred to as [[Great King]] by the Hittites hence he was the diplomatic equal of the Hittite king.<ref name="Hamblin" />

Yamhad was able to withstand the Hittite king [[Hattusili I]] aggressions through alliances with the Hurrians. Hattusili chose not to attack Halab directly and began with conquering Yamhad vassals and Allies, starting with Alalakh in the second year of his Syrian campaigns c. 1650 BC ([[Middle chronology]]) or slightly later.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=RTGc9YH-C38C&pg=PA97#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Near Eastern Art|author= Dominique Collon|page=97}}</ref> He then turned to attack the Hurrians in [[Urshu]] northeast of Halab and won in despite of Halab and Charchemish military support. After defeating Yamhad in a direct battle, Hattusili sacked [[Khashshum]] and several other Hurrian cities. 

After many campaigns Hattusili I finally attacked Halab during the reign of [[Hammurabi III]], the attack ended in a defeat,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=FF5-7JVj4jYC&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Cambridge Ancient History|author= Iorwerth Eiddon Stephen Edwards|page=33}}</ref> the wounding of the Hittite king and his later death in c. 1620 BC.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=q8Z7AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA29&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author= Trevor Bryce|page=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=azPl5Jzv930C&pg=PA107#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Historical Dictionary of the Hittites|author= Charles Burney|page=107}}</ref> Hattusili Campaigns considerably weakened Halab causing it to lose its status and the ruler of Yamhad ceased to be a Great King.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=Agg5-lpVI2MC&pg=PA152&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Kingdom of the Hittites|author= Trevor Bryce|page=152}}</ref>

Hattusili was succeeded by his grandchild [[Mursili I]] who conquered Halab in c. 1600 BC and destroyed Yamhad as a major power in the [[Levant]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=biyDDd0uKGMC&pg=PT256&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Warfare in the Ancient Near East to 1600 BC|author= William J. Hamblin| page=256}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=1A0OgvXfHlQC&pg=PA9#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ugarit in Retrospect: Fifty Years of Ugarit and Ugaritic|author= Gordon Douglas Young|page=9}}</ref> Mursili then left for [[Babylon]] and sacked it but was assassinated upon his return to his capital [[Hattusa]], his empire disintegrated which opened the way for the dynasty to continue. Halab was rebuilt and the kingdom expanded to include Alalakh again.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=Agg5-lpVI2MC&pg=PA126#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Kingdom of the Hittites |author= Trevor Bryce| page=126}}</ref> It was ruled by kings of which nothing but names is known, the first is [[Sarra-El]] who might have been the son of Yarim-Lim III.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=CMR5C12GOF8C&pg=PA382#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Orientalia: Vol. 38 |author= M.C. Astour| page=382}}</ref> The last king of the dynasty to rule as king of Halab was [[Ilim-Ilimma I]],<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=FF5-7JVj4jYC&pg=PA433#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Cambridge Ancient History|author=  Iorwerth Eiddon Stephen Edwards| page=433}}</ref> he was killed during a rebellion orchestrated by king [[Parshatatar]] of [[Mitanni]], his son [[Idrimi]] fled and was later able to take Alalakh and continued the line of kings there,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=RTGc9YH-C38C&pg=PA109#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Ancient Near Eastern Art|author= Dominique Collon| page=109}}</ref> while Halab lost its independence and stayed under the Mittanian rule.

Halab was taken by the Hittites during the reign of [[Suppiluliuma I]] in the 14th century BC who installed his son Telipinus as king of Halab but the use of the name Yamhad ended.

