==Economy==
Halab location has always been a factor in its prominence as an economic center, Yamhad economy was based on trade with [[Mesopotamia]] and [[Anatolia]], the city of [[Emar]],<ref name="Mario" /><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=_7kP_hNKHxIC&pg=PA23#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Representations of Political Power|author= Marlies Heinz,Marian H. Feldman|page= 23}}</ref> was Halab port on the [[Euphrates]], Alalakh with its proximity to the Sea was the port on the [[Mediterranean]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=_Vnqc4Ks4o4C&pg=PT46&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Hittites and Their World|author= Billie Jean Collins|page= 46}}</ref>

The actions of Yarim-Lim I proved vital for the kingdom economy, for he has secured the road between Babylon and Yamhad with his son in low the king of Mari protecting the caravans crossing from the [[Persian Gulf]] to [[Anatolia]].

Emar attracted many Babylonian merchants who lived in the city and had a lasting impact on the local scribal conventions since as late as the 14th-century BC texts of the so-called (Syrian type) from Emar preserve distinct Babylonian traits.

The invading of Mari by Babylon had a negative impact on trade between the two kingdoms as the road became dangerous because of the loss of Mari protection to the caravans crossing that road, which led [[Samsu-iluna]] to build strongholds up the river valley and to set colonies of mercenaries known as the Kassite Houses to protect the middle Euphrates area. Those colonies later evolved into semi independent polities that waged war against Babylonian king [[Ammi-Saduqa]] which caused the trade to stop temporarily.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=akYorRIWPBEC&pg=PA212#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Babylonian World|author= Gwendolyn Leick|page= 212}}</ref>

The markets of yamhad became a source of mountain (probably Anatolian) and Cypriot copper,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=akYorRIWPBEC&pg=PA213#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Babylonian World|author= Gwendolyn Leick|page= 213}}</ref> and economy remained prosperous until the Hittites Invasion in the beginning of the 16th century BC. Halab regained its economic status after the Hittites withdrawal and remained a Commercial center even after the end of Yamhad thanks to its location.

==People and culture==
The people of Yamhad were Amorites, spoke the [[Amorite language]] and belonged to the Amorite culture with Mesopotamian influence. Since Halab wasn't excavated, the architecture of the city can be imagined by looking into other cities in the area of that age, especially Alalakh which is the best archaeological representation of Yamhad,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=_7kP_hNKHxIC&pg=PA55#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Representations of Political Power|author= Marlies Heinz,Marian H. Feldman|page= 55}}</ref> and was subordinate to Halab with a king belonging to the Aleppan royal family. The Amorites in general built large palaces that bear architectural similarities to old Baylonian palaces that were adorned with grand central courtyards, throne rooms, tiled floors, drainage systems and plastered walls which suggest the employment of specialized labor, evidences exist for the presence of Minoan Aegean Frisco artists who painted elaborate scenes on the walls of palaces in Alalakh.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=5H4fAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT434#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Oxford Handbook of the Archaeology of the Levant: c. 8000-332 BCE|author= Margreet L. Steiner,Ann E. Killebrew|page= 409}}</ref>

Yamhad had a distinctive Syrian Iconography, Egyptian influence was minimum and limited to the [[Ankh]], the seals of kings gives prominence to Syrian gods, the use of the Ankh cannot be interpreted as an emulation of Egyptian rituals, it was merely a substitute to the cup held by the god.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=oiSoxUE_Vn0C&pg=PA38&lpg#v|title= Egyptian Iconography on Syro-Palestinian Cylinder Seals of the Middle Bronze Age|author= Beatrice Teissier|page= 38}}</ref>

Yamhad had a special pattern of trim called the Yamhad style and was favored in Mari during the reign of king Zimri-Lim whose queen was Shibtu the daughter of Yarim-Lim I.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=_oTh51M5XF4C&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Mari and Karana: Two Old Babylonian Cities|author= Stephanie Dalley|page= 51}}</ref>

After the fall of the Akkadian Empire, [[Hurrians]] began to settle in the city and its surroundings, blending with the [[Amorites]] and spreading their culture. by c. 1725 BC they constitute a sizable portion of the population.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=odCmAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Between Myth & Mandate|author= Michael Nathanson|page= 72}}</ref> the presence of large Hurrian population brought Hurrian culture and religion to Halab, evidenced by the worship of Hurrian gods [[Teshub]], his wife [[Hebat]] and certain religious festivals that bear Hurrian names.<ref name="Iorwerth">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=FF5-7JVj4jYC&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Cambridge Ancient History|author= Iorwerth Eiddon Stephen Edwards|page= 41}}</ref>

==Religion==
[[File:Udgravning (Citadellet Aleppo).jpg|thumb|Hadad Temple Inside [[Aleppo Citadel]] ]]
the people of Yamhad practiced the [[Canaanite religion|Amorite Religion]],<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=SgLxGuvnezUC&pg=PA896#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Oxford Handbook of the Archaeology of Ritual and Religion|author=  Timothy Insoll|page= 896}}</ref> with a Mesopotamian influence, they worshiped Semitic deities such as [[Astarte]] and [[Dagon]], but [[Hadad]] was the most important deity and the head of the [[Pantheon (gods)|Pantheon]],<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=xTE7o8aKI7IC&pg=PA121#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Religions of Second Millennium Anatolia|author= Piotr Taracha|page= 121}}</ref> he was known as the storm god of Halab since the middle of the 3rd millennium BC.

The main temple of Hadad was located on the citadel hill in the center of the city, it remained in use from the 24th century BC <ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=s9_lGE6jHawC&pg=PA166#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Muslim Military Architecture in Greater Syria|author= Hugh N. Kennedy|page= 166}}</ref> to at least the 9th century BC,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=hs1YQ-RO7lwC&pg=PA114#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Muqarnas|author= G<U+00FC>lru Necipo<U+011F>lu,Karen Leal|page= 114}}</ref> as evidenced by reliefs discovered at it during excavations by German archaeologist Kay Kohlmeyer.

the title Beloved of Hadad was one of the king titles,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=hM8UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Conflict Between El and Ba'al in Canaanite Religion|author= Ulf Oldenburg|page=67}}</ref> Hadad was the kingdom patron God, all treaties were Concluded in his name, he was used to threat other kingdoms<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=hM8UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Conflict Between El and Ba'al in Canaanite Religion|author= Ulf Oldenburg|page=160}}</ref> and to declare wars.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=ZGjcLBYTUUgC&pg=PA181#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Storm-god in the Ancient Near East|author= Alberto Ravinell Whitney Green|page= 181}}</ref>

Beside the general gods, kings had a ''Head God'', that is a God that has an intimate connection for the worshiper. king Yarim-Lim I describe Hadad as the god of the state but the Mesopotamian God [[Sin (mythology)|Sin]] as the god of his head so does his son Hammurabi I.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=VSJWkrXfbLQC&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Family Religion in Babylonia, Ugarit and Israel|author= K. Van Der Toorn|page= 77}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=VSJWkrXfbLQC&pg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Family Religion in Babylonia, Ugarit and Israel|author= K. Van Der Toorn|page= 88}}</ref>

As the hurrian presence grow, so did the hurrian religious effects, hurrian deities found a place in the Aleppan pantheon, king Abba-El I thanked hurrian Goddess hebat for his victory in one of Alalakh Tablets, Hebat was Teshub wife but in Abba-El I tablet she is associated with Hadad,<ref name="Iorwerth" /> later in history the hurrians started to identify Teshub with Hadad who became Teshub the storm god of Halab.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=ZGjcLBYTUUgC&pg=PA170#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= The Storm God in the Ancient Near East|author= Alberto Ravinell Whitney Green|page= 170}}</ref>

